<h1>Mall Directory Design Process</h1>
<div class='section_small'>
	<h3>Introduction</h3>
	<p>This project, which took under three months to finish, was completed in a course at UBC focused on Human-Computer Interaction. The main focus of the project was to find an existing system or software that has problems with its interface and find ways to improve upon it. During a brainstorming session for project ideas, my project team and I identified many problems with the existing static mall directory and we wanted to improve its usability. In the design process, we went through several iterations, from gathering user requirements, to low and medium-fidelity prototyping, to cognitive walkthroughs and user evaluations, and these are outlined below in more detail.</p>
</div> 
<div class='section_small'>
	<h3>Gathering User Requirements</h3>
	<p>We identified the main stakeholders to be mall shoppers, customer service workers and store managers. Through semi-structured interviews and questionnaires, we gathered the main user requirements that our stakeholders thought were important to include in our improved mall directory. These included:
	<ul>
		<li>an improvement in locating stores on a map without the use of arbitrary codes</li>
		<li>the ability to access the map wherever users are</li>
		<li>the use of colour and other indicators on mall map to help users locate stores</li>
		<li>the ability to search for shops that are available in the mall</li>
		<li>a map routing feature to quickly get to oneâ€™s desired destination</li>
		<li>the ability to adapt map routing to work on multi-level story malls</li>
	</ul>
	<p>After gathering and prioritizing all the user requirements, we felt that creating a mobile application would be the best choice for several reasons. First, the smartphone adoption rate is rising rapidly, and based on our surveys, many shoppers wanted to have the ability to access the mall map wherever they are in the mall instead of having to look for the map. Also, it allows for enhanced functionality such as the ability to search and find the quickest route to specific stores. Since we are creating a mobile application, it could also provide stores another way of offering promotions and communicating sales and products directly to shoppers. Overall, it would be great addition to the static mall directories that already exist in malls. </p>
</div>
<div class='section_small'>
	<h3>Design Process, Prototyping and User Evaluation Results</h3>
	<p>After committing to designing a mobile application, my team and I started designing prototypes through an iterative process. After each stage of prototyping, we administered user evaluations to get feedback so that we can continually improve on our designs and that the end result would satisfy our user requirements. Shown below are some highlights of the prototype, as well as user feedback garnered from our evaluations, and improvements needed in future iterations. When conducting user evaluations, we gave participants different tasks and observed how well they were able to accomplish them, and recorded any comments they provided.</p>
